Ask HN: Why aren't there popular services using data exports of social networks?
text:
When Facebook, Instagram, Twitter and other platforms started to offer data exports (even more so on pressure from GDPR) I became excited that there will be great efforts to build upon them, do things with the data that these networks were not incentivised to do. See a timeline where all social media activity is visible at once, see patterns, persons in your life throughout the years, or even migrate to new platforms by importing all your existing messages, content. The data is wast, and easily usable.

Apart from experimental small scripts I couldn't find any projects like the above. Do some legal terms explicitly forbid to use them in this way? Is there really such a disinterest from the dev community to work with this data?

To note: yes, handling such data is a huge privacy risk, but a) these could be offline/self-hosted tools b) if someone trusted the same data to these platforms, why couldn't he entrust them with other more open/transparent/appealing platforms.

Ask HN: How do you monitor your Slack bots?
text:
I am working on a Slack bot and wondering if there are any tools or best practices to setup end-to-end monitoring for Slack bots and integrations.

For example, I would like to assert that my service responds correctly to slash commands and the response is sent within the 3 sec threshold. There are few other monitoring scenarios like monitoring outbound notifications.

Talking to few of my friends who previously worked on Slack integrations, apart from log monitoring they did not setup end-to-end monitoring for their flows.

Appreciate any feedback/comments on how you monitor your Slack related functionality.

Ask HN: Are companies becoming increasingly pushy? If so why?
text:
I don't remember the timeline. I believe browsing Pinterest anonymously was always limited, therefore I pretty much always avoided this site. At some point LinkedIn changed to require a login to view profiles, well most of the time. Maybe this change occurred around the time Microsoft bought them. I avoid LinkedIn too. At some point both Instagram and Twitter also started aggressively limiting content for anonymous users. Medium and Substack have been increasingly nagging and/or limiting content too. Spotify seems to be trying to increasingly cross sell podcasts and audio books. Just within the last week they've also made multiple attempts to get me to enable push notifications for various communication. And then just this morning I browsed Indeed to keep an eye on what's going on in the local area and found they are limiting search results to one page without logging in. The only one of these I pay for is Spotify, so I guess fair enough, except for Spotify. This certainly isn't a comprehensive list. I feel I'm having to be increasingly defensive. I'm finding I'm spending more and more time blocking, dismissing or having to give up on sites and services.

Is this trend increasing? If so what are some reasons why this is occurring? Is it the changing economy? Because companies dominate the product and so they feel they can get away with it? Because companies grow and lose their first principles? Because of the pressure to always be growing?

I'm interested in hearing the thoughts of others on this topic? Is this behavior increasing? What is contributing to it? Is this something we will need to learn to accept or is this something to contest? Is there a positive aspect to this, such as this behavior will create opportunities for other players?

Show HN: Chipscribe: A platform for people to split the cost of subscriptions
text:
Hi,

I know everyone on HN is an elite programmer making tons of money. However, in the current market idk anymore, but as a student money is short and I split the cost of basically all my subscriptions with my roommates from Netflix to Spotify. Over the summer I thought what if I make a platform that allows anyone to split the cost of subscriptions with random people anywhere in the country and save everyone a buck or two in the process, they wouldn't have to listen to the gurus about canceling all their favorite streaming subscriptions so I made chipscribe(my first website btw so its a bit rough especially the landing page. Most of my time was spent automating account creation and management on sites like Netflix) and I wanted to share it. although, there's not much atm.

Ask HN: An Ideal Project Task Manager?
text:
I am looking for a project task manager with the following features (example).

---

Tasks, Sub Tasks (Graph), Recurring Tasks

- Add notes related to task (TickTick).

- Assign tasks to users or vice versa (ClickUp).

- Automatic addition of tasks to calendar when date is mentioned (Taskade).

---

Organization

- Projects

- Lists

- Tags

- etc

* Multiple views for each task list (Taskade).

---

Time Tracking

- Recording, Manual Entry (Toggl)

- Reports (Toggl)

- Activity Log (optional)

---

Suggest applications that are file-based (offline usage) or self-hosted (open source), AND/OR that provide ANY of the requested features using CalDav (but remain file-based or self-hosted).

Please don't recommend single user linux command line * (like orgmode or taskwarrior).
